{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17565239","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17565239"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:24:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:24:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17274"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17274","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17274"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.89,0.01,0.02,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9964"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78690"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9964","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9964"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17274"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64033"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"548"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23351"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26222"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26671"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78690","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78690"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a lesion on her nose that has been slowly growing over the past eight months. She works as a retired gardener and has a history of extensive sun exposure. She has a medical history of hypertension and osteoarthritis, for which she takes amlodipine and paracetamol. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a 1 cm pearly nodule with surface telangiectasia on the left lateral aspect of her nose (Image). The lesion is non-tender and does not bleed.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Squamous cell carcinoma","Basal cell carcinoma","Sebaceous hyperplasia","Dermatofibroma","Melanoma"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of a \u003Cstrong\u003Ebasal cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E (BCC). This is the most common skin cancer, typically presenting as a slow-growing, pearly nodule with telangiectatic vessels. Rolled edges and ulcerations is also commonly seen (image 1). The nose is one of the most common sites due to chronic sun exposure. The patient\u0027s history as a gardener with extensive sun exposure is a significant risk factor.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESquamous cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents as a firm, scaly or crusted plaque or nodule that may ulcerate. It tends to grow more rapidly than BCC and often has a rougher, more keratotic surface. Here is an example (Image 2).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESebaceous hyperplasia\u003C/strong\u003E presents as small (2-3 mm), soft, pale yellow papules with central umbilication. While common on the face, these lesions are typically multiple and do not continue to grow.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDermatofibroma\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents as a firm brown nodule that dimples when squeezed laterally. It is more common on the legs and rarely occurs on the face. Here is an example (Image 3).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMelanoma\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents as a pigmented lesion with irregular borders, colour variation, and asymmetry (image 4). The pearly appearance and telangiectasia described in this case are not typical features of melanoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Basal cell carcinoma typically presents as a pearly nodule with telangiectasia and rolled edges.","The nose is a high-risk site for basal cell carcinoma due to sun exposure.","Risk factors for basal cell carcinoma include advanced age, fair skin, and occupational sun exposure."],"references":["Arasu A, Meah N, Sinclair R. Skin checks in primary care. Australian Journal for General Practitioners. 2019 Aug 29;48:614\u20139."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64033"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17274"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21443"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21454"},{"type":"media","id":"21455"},{"type":"media","id":"21456"},{"type":"media","id":"21457"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21443","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21443"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/50pCZibO9OqJGUT7D9rYxGjTJo3zH2.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/50pCZibO9OqJGUT7D9rYxGjTJo3zH2.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":318,"height":440}},{"type":"media","id":"21454","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21454"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/t49uHgdc7CGAJTcE1Wn8ZXzERak5uZ.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/t49uHgdc7CGAJTcE1Wn8ZXzERak5uZ.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":290,"height":440}},{"type":"media","id":"21455","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21455"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/NNv6tULmQ30WzGF5Bo96NlMzLJxMw9.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/NNv6tULmQ30WzGF5Bo96NlMzLJxMw9.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":1125}},{"type":"media","id":"21456","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21456"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/t0vXD1Hvo0sWio5Pnw722mtods3qO0.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/s